observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the BLGUs of Kaumbakan, Hañib and Uvoy to immediately require the submission of the necessary liquidation reports and supporting documents of the transferred funds totaling to ₱1.030 million;
Investigate the causes of the delays and extend help to BLGUs to implement the activity/project specially the purchase of lot for BLGU Kaumbakan; If the activity/project is not possible or not implemented, require the BLGUs for the refund of funds;
Immediately record the liquidation of ₱0.500 million in the books of accounts to correct the overstatement in the "Due from LGUs" account;
Conduct periodic monitoring of fund utilization and corresponding liquidations from recipient barangays to prevent similar occurrences; and
Direct the personnel responsible for reviewing and monitoring commitments and agreements with partner agencies to clearly define project implementation timelines in the MOA, including the start date, completion date, and reporting deadlines, to prevent delays and ensure efficient fund utilization. Also, ensure that the date of signing by both parties is explicitly stated. Lastly, submit a clear copy of the signed MOA to this Office for monitoring and reference.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to immediately conduct reconciliation of records and assess the actual completion of the 18 reported fully completed projects costing ₱28.936 million and the projects with variance of ₱9.177 million;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Reclassify, based on sufficient documentation, the fully completed projects from CIP to the appropriate PPE accounts;
Develop and enforce internal controls and monitoring mechanisms to ensure timely reclassification of completed projects from CIP to PPE and proper recognition of obligations to contractors and suppliers; and
Direct the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to exert efforts to identify the projects with lacking details, determine its commencement, completion and status. Otherwise, include these items in the one-time cleansing of PPE balances following the procedures and guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately revert the long outstanding AP amounting to ₱1.494 million to the unappropriated surplus. Accordingly, prepare a journal entry by debiting AP and crediting Government Equity for the said amount;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with GDP TRADING relative to the outstanding payable of ₱0.173 million and determine the propriety of settling the liabilities in accordance with rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct review and assessment of the unaccounted transactions and prepare the necessary adjusting entry, if applicable; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly disclose in the NFS all the contingent liability arising from the undelivered POs at year-end to ensure the fair presentation of the FS.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Immediately record the received amount of ₱0.845 million from the DOH-CVCHD and the disbursements of ₱6.990 million and ₱9.086 million from the NGAs and LGUs and recognize the “Other Deferred Credits” of ₱16.076 million in accordance with the accrual basis of accounting prescribed under IPSAS 1 to reflect the actual receipt and utilization of funds;
For future transactions, coordinate promptly with the source agencies to secure all necessary supporting documents, such as the DVs and LDDAP-ADAs, in the absence of the corresponding NADAI, to ensure the timely and proper recording of transactions in the books of accounts;
Conduct a detailed review of the unaccounted balance of ₱15.033 million and ₱69,688.37 from the accounts “Due to NGAs” and “Due to LGUs”, respectively, including tracing the source, purpose, and utilization history of these amounts. Also, correct the misclassification of the Tourism Unified Fee transactions by adjusting the entries to reflect both the receipts and disbursements under the appropriate account. If the fund is determined to be stale, untraceable, or no longer valid, initiate the refund or write-off process in accordance with the procedures prescribed under COA Circular Nos. 2016-005 and 2023-008, whichever is applicable;
Determine the applicable guidelines relative to the fund transfers for prizes amounting ₱25,000.00 from DOH-CVCHD by coordinating with the respective agencies for proper treatment and reclassification of the funds;
Coordinate with DOH-CVCHD to obtain the MOA for the project 2014 HFEP Completion of Diura Barangay Health Station amounting ₱0.250 million which was transferred on March 1, 2019. If unavailable, formally request a certified copy or a notarized statement from the agency explaining the status of the agreements;
Strictly adhere to Sections 4.6 and 4.9 of COA Circular No. 94-013 by ensuring the preparation of Liquidation Reports on a monthly basis for all received funds, regardless of whether transactions have occurred, and promptly submit within the prescribed period to this Office and the respective Source Agencies. Also, indicate the date prepared, and proper report number in all Liquidation Reports to ensure completeness, traceability, and audit trail integrity. Relative thereto, assign a personnel to monitor the timely submission of the same;
Strengthen financial monitoring mechanisms by conducting periodic reconciliations with Source Agencies to ensure that reported balances are accurate and up to date; and
Require the personnel in-charge in the review and monitoring of commitments and agreements with partner-agencies to clearly specify project implementation timelines, including the start date, completion date, and reporting deadlines, to prevent delays and promote efficient fund utilization. Additionally, ensure that the date of signing by both parties is explicitly indicated in the MOA and notarized. A clear copy of the signed MOA shall be submitted to this Office for proper monitoring and reference.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the supply officer designated in the LDRRM storage facilities to properly arrange the relief goods such that essential food and non-food items are grouped, labeled, and organized, and maintain updated stock cards for each kind of relief goods;
Direct the removal of the highly flammable item away from the storage room and strictly store it in a well-ventilated area, away from heat, sparks, and ignition sources;
Direct the LDRRMO to transfer the boxes of sardines to a secured and locked area and ensure that access is available only to authorized personnel;
Instruct the LDRRMO to determine the feasibility and propriety of distributing the undistributed commercial rice under the food for work program to reduce wastage; and
Ensure that relief goods are properly managed and safeguarded against loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
Require the MEO to timely conduct the detailed engineering activities of Infrastructure projects, especially for those to be implemented “By Administration”, to preclude the recurrence of non-inclusion of the general components in the indicative PPMP during the Budget Preparation Phase, thereby increasing the CY 20% DF utilization rate at year-end;
Require the reviewing personnel/bodies and the local sanggunian to rigorously evaluate the propriety, accuracy and completeness of each Department’s budget proposals, to ensure that only relevant, responsive and feasible items are to be funded and implemented out of the 20% DF. Accordingly, all infrastructure projects shall be supported with POW and DED during the presentation of Budget Proposals;
Require the implementing offices to propose projects that are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready. Henceforth, consider the inflation rate and history of prices to reflect a more current and responsive program/project costing thus precluding the incurrence of loss for the LGU and maximum utilization of funds can be achieved;
Require the MPDO, together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Local Finance Committee, to conduct a periodic review and assessment of the financial and physical status of the PPAs determine on a timely basis the possible declaration of savings which will be reappropriated for other development projects under the 20% DF, and formulate catch-up plans for slow-moving PPAs to avoid further delays in the implementation;
Direct the implementing offices, to communicate with the regulating agencies to expedite the acquisition of the required clearances. Accordingly, Management shall endeavor to complete all the appropriate preparatory activities such as, but not limited to, cost-benefit analysis, feasibility studies, market research, and detailed engineering designs, regulatory clearances to preclude delays in the implementation of the PPAs; and
Require the implementing offices, in coordination with Accounting Office, to fast track the preparation of necessary documents for claims that are due and demandable, thereby increasing the utilization rate of the PPAs as of year-end.

We recommended that Management:
Shall endeavor to develop a balanced procurement plan that allocates resources to boost LDRRM overall response in the long run by considering investment in infrastructure projects such as permanent evacuation center based on national standard, logistic hub/warehouse facility and other similar LDRRM-related projects;
Discontinue the utilization of LDRRM Fund for activities or events that do not align with the primary purpose of addressing disaster-related needs of the LGU;
Require the implementing office, in coordination with BAC, to adopt a more dynamic procurement strategy aligned with weather forecasts and historical data on weather patterns in the locality to ensure the sufficiency and immediate availability of LDRRM-related items, when needed. Accordingly, for welfare food items Management shall endeavor to enter into Framework/Ordering Agreement with prospective suppliers and “Call-off” may be executed and issued to the winning supplier immediately upon the determination that an item is needed, pursuant to the guidelines under Annex 32 of the RIRR of Republic Act No. 9184 otherwise known as the Government Procurement Reform Act. With this, lean and just-in-time procurements are achieved and the limited storage facilities of the LGU can be maximized;
Utilize the stock card in the inventory management to ensure that welfare goods are available and in optimal condition when required. Similarly, ensure the timely and proper disposal of nearly expiring goods/items through the identified modality by the LGU, to preclude any wastage of government funds;
Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage;
Require the MDRRMO to provide an explanation/justification why the ₱23,106.00 provision for “Contingency” which was identified as loss incurred by the Municipality should not be disallowed in audit;
Require the implementing office, in coordination with Bid and Awards Committee and Budget Office, to consider the inflation rate and history of prices to reflect a more current and responsive program/project costing thus precluding the incurrence of loss for the LGU and maximum utilization of funds can be achieved;
Discontinue the practice of inclusion of “Contingency” as line item in the procurement planning, to preclude the issuance of Audit Disallowance;
Require the implementing office, in coordination with BAC for purposes of monitoring compliance, to timely identify the component items of the crafted PPAs and religiously submit the corresponding PPMPs to the BAC Secretariat for consolidation or updating of APP; and
Require the MDRRMO to thoroughly review and update annually or as may be required, those irrelevant PPAs included in the LDRRMFIP that do not respond to present needs and circumstances, to prevent funds to become idle and deprivation of the constituents of the benefits that could be derived therefrom.

Submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact;
Henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPs Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
Instruct the BAC to specify in the RFQ under the General Instructions portion the evaluation method for submitted bids and indicating whether the contract will be awarded on a per item, whole lot, or by several lots. Subsequently, ensure that the ABC reflected in the RFQ accurately corresponds to the chosen bid evaluation method, providing comprehensive information to interested bidder-suppliers about the bid ceiling;
Henceforth, require the BAC to religiously adhere to the required number of responsive quotations to be obtained under the chosen Alternative Mode of Procurement and strictly follow the procedures set forth therein;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that posting requirements of RFQ, Notice of Award, PO/Contract and Notice to Proceed, if necessary, on all procurement through shopping with ABC higher than ₱50,000.00 are complied with and proof thereof are attached to the disbursement voucher to establish correctness of information and reliability of bidding process;
Ensure that all regulatory permits, registrations and licenses are available and up-to-date prior to engaging the services of individuals and businesses. If unavailable, encourage the prospective suppliers to secure permits and comply other registration requirements such as Mayor’s Permit, BIR and PhilGEPS registrations etc., to ensure eligibility in future procurement endeavors with the LGU-Mahatao; and
Carefully review the most appropriate mode of procurement to be undertaken to promote economy of time and resources.

We recommended that Management:
a. Submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on traveling expense representing cost of inland transportation which were noted as non-compliant with EO 77, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
b.  Discontinue the charging of costs for inland transportation during official travels;
Require printed receipts to support the claim for taxi fares of its employees and ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to every disbursement to preclude the issuance of Audit Suspension or Disallowance;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to require personnel of the LGU claiming traveling expenses to submit complete travel documents set forth under COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and further updated by COA Circular 2023-004 dated June 14, 2023, to preclude the issuance of Notice of Suspension or Disallowance; and
Establish internal local and foreign travel policy guidelines that are reasonably fair, cost-effective and aligns with the financial capability of the LGU subject to compliance with the provisions of EO 77.

We recommended that Management:
a.  Include as a priority project the establishment of a room/building which shall serve as the storage facility for procured property and inventories prior to the release to end-user units. Relative to this, Management shall endeavor to maintain a centralized inventory management system;
Pending the establishment of a storage room/warehouse, the Municipal Mayor shall designate employees per department, who shall manage the issuance, recording and reporting of inventories in their respective offices;
Require the proper utilization of the stock cards at the office-level in the monitoring of supplies and materials;
Require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the end-user units and the General Services Officer to conduct an inventory count on all office supplies that are yet to be consumed as of a cut-off date to be determined by the Committee and prepare RPCI for recording and control purposes. Henceforth, conduct the required physical count and submit to the Auditor the report thereon not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Based on the RPCI prepared, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the cost of Inventories at hand and henceforth observe the proper accounting policies and entries in the recording of transactions; and
Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage

We recommended that Management:
require the Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to reconcile the inventory count report and the accounting records. Investigate and evaluate the differences, adjust the records as appropriate and submit a revised RPCPPE based on the reconciliations made;
require the Inventory Committee to analyze the nature of the items included in the RPCPPE and classify them according to the appropriate and specific PPE account titles prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts;
direct the Agency’s appraisal committee to determine the fair value of the donated items identified and furnish the Accounting Office with the Appraisal Report for the recording thereof;
require the Municipal Accountant to identify the recorded PPE items that failed to meet the P15,000.00 capitalization threshold and prepare appropriate adjusting entries; and
prioritize the strict implementation and enforcement of the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that Management:
include as a priority project the establishment of a room/building which shall serve as the storage facility for procured property and inventories prior to the release to end-user units. Relative to this, Management shall endeavor to maintain a centralized inventory management system;
pending the establishment of a storage room/warehouse, the Municipal Mayor shall designate employees, who shall be properly bonded, to manage the issuance, recording and reporting of inventories in their respective offices;
require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the end-user units and the General Services Officer to conduct an inventory count on all office supplies that are yet to be consumed as of a cut-off date to be determined by the Committee and prepare a Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) for recording and control purposes. Henceforth, conduct the required physical count and submit to the Auditor the report thereon not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
based on the RPCI prepared, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the cost of Inventories at hand and henceforth observe the proper accounting policies and entries in the recording of transactions; and
ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
require the BAC to submit, for each procurement project, the identified lacking documents to support the procurement activities conducted and establish the reliability of the bidding process, otherwise, provide justifications/explanations for the absence thereof;
direct the Inspection Officer and the former Property Officer, based on verifiable evidence, to identify the actual dates of deliveries of the goods procured through public bidding, in the total amount of P10,976,916.00;
based on the information to be obtained from the Inspection Officer and the former Property Officer, the Municipal Accountant shall ascertain on a per contract basis, whether or not delay in the delivery of procured items exists, compute the applicable liquidated damages thereon, as warranted and withhold the same from the future payments to the identified suppliers;
henceforth, require the Municipal Accountant and the Inspection Committee to ensure completeness and correctness of information (e.g. date of report, date of acceptance, date of inspection) contained in the Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) which may serve as a tool in the computation of possible liquidated damages to be imposed to the suppliers with delayed deliveries;
direct the BAC to transmit to the Office of the Auditor, within five days after the execution of the contract, all documents to support the perfection thereof as  enumerated in COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012. A list of the documents submitted shall accompany the transmittal for ease of verification. Accordingly, a copy of the COA-received transmittal shall form part of the integral supporting documents in the processing of the related disbursement vouchers; and
submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit.

We recommended that Management:
submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to reflect the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) of a particular procurement project in the Request for Quotation (RFQ) to ensure that the interested bidder-supplier is adequately informed of the ceiling of the bid;
henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPS Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
henceforth, require the submission of BAC resolution recommending award of contract to the supplier with lowest quotation which complies with the specifications and other terms and conditions stated in the RFQ as additional basis of the Head of Agency to enter into contract with the said supplier;
direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that posting requirements of RFQ, Notice of Award, Purchase Order/Contract and Notice to Proceed if necessary, on all procurement through shopping with ABC higher than P50,000.00 are complied with and proof thereof are attached to the disbursement voucher to establish correctness of information and reliability of bidding process;
henceforth, carefully review the reasonableness of all requests for time extension for the delivery of goods which shall be made prior to the expiration of the original term. Relative to this, the period of extension shall be clearly stated in the request and the approval or disapproval thereof shall be promptly communicated to the supplier. Management shall avoid approving extensions for a period more than the original contract time;
direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact; and
require the Municipal Accountant to submit the original copies of the unsubmitted Purchase Orders identified.

We recommended the following courses of actions:
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Office with the complete description and cost segregation of road component for road projects;
The GSO or inventory team submit Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
The GSO and Municipal Accountant maintain the required Local Road Network Property and Ledger Cards, respectively.
The Accounting Office prepare the Journal Voucher to record the local road network and its component in the books of accounts.

